```cpp
#include <iostream>

// Function to find the nth Fibonacci number using recursion
unsigned long long fibonacci(unsigned int n) {
    if (n <= 1) {
        return n;
    }
    return fibonacci(n - 1) + fibonacci(n - 2);
}

int main() {
    unsigned int n;
    std::cout << "Enter the value of n to find the nth Fibonacci number: ";
    std::cin >> n;

    // Calculate the nth Fibonacci number
    unsigned long long nthFibonacci = fibonacci(n);

    // Output the result
    std::cout << "The " << n << "th Fibonacci number is: " << nthFibonacci << std::endl;

    return 0;
}
```

To compile and run this program, you would typically use a command like `g++ -o fibonacci fibonacci.cpp` and then `./fibonacci` to execute it on a Unix-like system.

Please note that this recursive approach is not efficient for large values of `n` because it recalculates the same Fibonacci numbers multiple times. For large values of `n`, an iterative approach or memoization (caching previously calculated Fibonacci numbers) would be more efficient.

